# What Is Pragmatics? The Hidden Operating System

## The Pragmatics Learning Hub for Autistic Individuals

> Pragmatics is the layer of communication that isn't about the words. It has mechanics, patterns, and names -- and it can be learned as a system, not guessed as an intuition.

---

## How to Read This Page

This is the entry point to the whole hub. You don't need any prior reading to start here. If a section goes fast, come back to it -- everything on this page gets unpacked in detail elsewhere.

This page has one job: to make a thing called **pragmatics** visible, and to reframe what it means to have spent your life noticing that something was happening in conversations that you couldn't quite see.

---

## 1. The Experience

### 1.1 The Moment You've Probably Had

You said the right thing. You know you said the right thing, because you checked the words. The words were accurate. The words were appropriate to the topic. The words answered the question that was asked. And then something went wrong anyway.

Someone's face changed. Or the conversation got cooler. Or a person you thought you were getting along with stopped replying. Or a manager used the word "tone" in your review and you had no idea what they were referring to because the words of the thing you said were fine.

You went back over it later. You ran the transcript in your head. The sentence was correct. The grammar was correct. The information was true. You answered the actual question. And yet.

This is the experience the hub exists to address. It is not your imagination. Something really did happen that you didn't see. And the thing you didn't see has a name.

### 1.2 A Few Small Examples

Here are five tiny moments. Don't worry about the technical names yet -- just notice that something is going on in each one that isn't in the literal words.

**Example 1.** Your partner asks, "Do you know what time it is?" You say, "Yes." They look annoyed. You weren't being sarcastic. You answered the question they asked -- whether you know the time. But that wasn't really the question they asked.

**Example 2.** A coworker says, "It's a little cold in here, don't you think?" You say, "It's fine for me." They sigh. You didn't realize they were asking you to close the window. Their sentence was about temperature; their message was about the window.

**Example 3.** You're at a party. Someone says, "We should hang out sometime!" You say, "Sure, how about next Tuesday at 7?" They become uncomfortable. You later learn that "we should hang out sometime" was, for them, a friendly closing phrase -- not an actual proposal to schedule anything.

**Example 4.** A friend tells you about a hard day at work. You respond by analyzing the problem and suggesting three solutions. They get upset. They wanted, it turns out, for you to say "that sounds really hard" first. The solutions could come later, or maybe not at all.

**Example 5.** Your manager says, "When you have a chance, it would be great if you could look at the Johnson file." You take it as information about her preferences. Two days later she asks, with an edge in her voice, whether you've looked at the Johnson file yet. You thought she was making a low-priority request. She thought she was giving you a deadline.

### 1.3 The Invisible Layer

In every one of those examples, the words were doing one thing and the speaker was doing another. "Do you know what time it is?" is, on the surface, a question about your knowledge. In practice, in that context, between those people, it was a request for the time. "It's a little cold in here" was, on the surface, a comment about temperature. In practice, it was a request to close the window. "We should hang out sometime" was, on the surface, a proposal. In practice, it was a friendly goodbye.

There are two layers running in every conversation: the layer made of words, and the layer made of what you're **supposed to mean** by choosing those specific words in this specific situation with this specific person. Most communication in adult life runs on the second layer. The first layer is mostly a carrier signal for the second.

The second layer is what linguists call **pragmatics**. It is not a mysterious social grace. It is not an intuition you were supposed to be born with. It is a system -- a hidden operating system running underneath the words -- and it has rules, patterns, and mechanisms that can be named, mapped, and learned.

That is what this hub exists to do: make the hidden layer visible.

### 1.4 What You Probably Already Noticed

If you are an autistic adult reading this, there is a strong chance you already knew, in some form, that this second layer existed. You noticed that people seemed to mean things they didn't say. You noticed that answers to questions were judged by something other than whether they were accurate. You noticed that the same sentence went over well in one room and badly in another and you couldn't figure out the variable.

You may have been told that what you were noticing was "social skills" and that other people just *had* them. You may have tried to fix this by memorizing rules, or by masking, or by going quiet, or by over-preparing scripts for conversations that then went off-script in the first ten seconds. None of that is a failure of intelligence. It is a perfectly reasonable response to being asked to run software you were never given the documentation for.

This hub is the documentation.

---

## 2. What Pragmatics Is

### 2.1 A Working Definition

**Pragmatics** is the branch of linguistics that studies how context contributes to meaning. It is the study of what speakers mean, as distinct from what their words say.

The easiest way to hold the distinction is this:

- **Semantics** is about the meaning of sentences in the abstract. "It's cold in here" means that the temperature in this location is low.
- **Pragmatics** is about what a speaker is **doing** when they say that sentence in a particular situation. "It's cold in here," said to the person nearest the window, with a small glance at the window, is usually a request to close the window.

Semantics gives you the literal content. Pragmatics gives you the action the content is being used to perform.

### 2.2 A Brief History

Pragmatics emerged as a field in the middle of the 20th century. Three figures are worth knowing at the start.

**J.L. Austin** (Oxford philosopher, 1950s). Austin noticed that some sentences don't describe reality -- they *do* things in it. "I promise" doesn't report a promise; it makes one. "I now pronounce you married" doesn't describe a marriage; it creates one. His book, *How to Do Things with Words* (1962), is the founding text of **speech act theory** -- the idea that every utterance is an action, not just information.

**John Searle** (1969, 1975). Searle extended Austin's work into a systematic theory. He gave us the distinction between **direct** speech acts (where the form matches the function) and **indirect** speech acts (where they don't). "Can you pass the salt?" is a question in form and a request in function. That mismatch -- and the rules that govern it -- is Searle's enduring contribution.

**H.P. Grice** (1967, published 1975). Grice asked a different question: if so much of what we mean is not in what we say, how does anyone ever figure out what anyone else means? His answer was the **Cooperative Principle** -- the assumption that speakers are generally trying to communicate sensibly -- and the set of conversational **maxims** (roughly: be informative, be truthful, be relevant, be clear). When a speaker seems to violate a maxim, listeners don't conclude the speaker is broken; they conclude that the speaker is *implying* something beyond the literal words. That inferred meaning is called an **implicature**, and it is the engine that powers most everyday indirection.

These three -- Austin, Searle, Grice -- built the foundation. Everything else in the hub extends, critiques, or applies their work.

### 2.3 The Four Systems You'll Meet First

Most of the hub's early categories cluster around four subsystems. You'll meet them in depth in Categories 1 through 4. Here is a first look.

**Speech acts** (Category 1). What an utterance is *doing*. Requesting, refusing, promising, warning, apologizing, complimenting, asserting, questioning. The same sentence can perform different acts in different contexts, and the same act can be performed by many different sentences. The autistic-relevant insight: if you only track the words, you will miss the action.

**Implicature** (Category 2). What a speaker means beyond what they literally say. "It's getting late" at a dinner party is rarely a statement about time. "Some of the team agreed" usually implies that not all of them did. Implicature is Grice's invention and it is the single most common source of pragmatic mismatch between autistic and non-autistic speakers.

**Politeness** (Category 3). The system of linguistic strategies speakers use to manage each other's social standing -- what Brown and Levinson (1987) called **face**. Indirect requests, hedges, apologies, compliments, and softened refusals are all politeness moves. The autistic-relevant insight: politeness is not about being "nice." It is a machinery with specific moves and specific costs, and it can be read like a grammar.

**Conversation structure** (Category 4). The mechanics of how conversations are built: how turns are taken, how topics are opened and closed, how interruptions work, how repair happens when something goes wrong. Turn-taking is not the free-for-all it looks like from the outside. It is structured, rule-governed, and learnable.

Those four form the core. The hub's other categories -- discourse markers, hedging, register, deixis, presupposition, relevance, non-literal language, narrative, topic management, and the rest -- all build on them.

---

## 3. Why This Matters for Autistic Adults

### 3.1 The Reframe

Here is the single most important sentence on this page:

**Nobody learns pragmatics naturally. Most people pick it up through exposure, and some people need explicit instruction -- and that's a difference in teaching, not a difference in capability.**

This reframe matters because the standard story -- the one most autistic adults have been told implicitly or explicitly their whole lives -- is that pragmatics is something typical children *just absorb*, and that failing to absorb it is a kind of developmental fault. That story is wrong in two important ways.

First, typical children don't absorb pragmatics from thin air. They absorb it from thousands of hours of social feedback, most of which is calibrated to their specific neurocognitive profile. The adults around them are, without realizing it, teaching pragmatics by modeling it, reacting to it, and repairing breakdowns in ways that make sense to a typical child's attention and salience systems. That is instruction. It just doesn't look like instruction, because the curriculum is invisible.

Second, when the learner's neurocognitive profile is different, the same environment doesn't deliver the same lesson. The social feedback is still happening, but it is less legible -- less predictable, less attached to obvious cues, more dependent on implicit cues that the autistic learner's attention may not have landed on. The implicit channel is narrower. And the explicit channel -- actual, spoken-aloud instruction in "here is what 'we should hang out sometime' means and here is how to answer it" -- is almost never offered, because the adults around the child don't know they are experts in a system with a name.

Put those two together and you get the actual situation: autistic adults have often missed pragmatic content through no failure of theirs, because the only instruction offered was implicit, and the implicit channel was narrower for them. The gap is real. The gap is not a deficit. The gap is a teaching gap.

### 3.2 The Double Empathy Problem

The reframe goes one step further. It is not only that autistic people were under-taught a system. It is that the system itself is one of *several* possible pragmatic systems, and autistic communication tends to run on a different one.

Damian Milton (2012) named this the **double empathy problem**. The core claim: communication breakdowns between autistic and non-autistic people are **bidirectional**. Both parties are operating with pragmatic expectations the other side doesn't share. Both parties are making inferences that turn out to be wrong. Both parties walk away feeling that something went off. The breakdown is mutual.

What happens next is asymmetric, though. The mismatch gets charged to the autistic side by default. The autistic person is the one who "missed the tone," "took it wrong," "didn't read the room," "lacks theory of mind." The non-autistic person is rarely described as "failing to interpret an autistic communicator." The data is clear that autistic-to-autistic communication works smoothly for many of the same pairs who get labeled "socially impaired" in mixed-neurotype conversation (Crompton et al., 2020). The problem isn't one broken brain. It's two systems meeting and only one of them getting blamed.

The double empathy problem is load-bearing for the whole hub. It is the reason the hub teaches pragmatics as a **second language** rather than as a corrective therapy. You are learning the conventions of a communication style that is one option among several. You are not being fixed. You are getting access to documentation for a system you have to interact with.

> **Go deeper**: [Tier 1 -- Double Empathy](tier-1-double-empathy.md) unpacks Milton's 2012 paper, the replication studies, and what the bidirectional framing means for how you read the rest of the hub.

### 3.3 What This Changes

If pragmatics is a learnable system, several things follow.

It means that the feeling of "I missed something that everyone else got" is explainable without being pathological. You missed something because it wasn't taught. You can now read the documentation.

It means that you are allowed to learn pragmatics the way you learn other systems: by studying the mechanics, mapping the patterns, and practicing the moves you choose to practice. You do not have to absorb it through osmosis. Osmosis was never how it worked for anyone; it was just more efficient for typical cognition.

It means that you get to decide, once you understand the system, how much of it you want to use. Knowing how a politeness strategy works does not obligate you to perform it. Understanding an indirect request does not mean you have to make indirect requests yourself. The point of learning the operating system is so that you are no longer running it blind -- not so that you become a different kind of person.

---

## 4. The Hub's Core Commitments

These are the promises the hub makes to you. They are not aspirational; they are the conditions under which every page is written.

### 4.1 Neurodiversity-Affirming

Autistic communication is a difference in how minds work, not a deficit to be corrected. The hub treats autistic communication as a legitimate mode, teaches pragmatics as a second language rather than a remedial one, and refuses the language of disorder and impairment throughout. You will not find "autism spectrum disorder" as the default frame here; you will find "autistic adults" and "autistic communication." 

This is _not_ a refutation of autism as a disability. It _is_ a disability. But not all parts of autism must be framed as pathological. This hub operates under the assumption that many of the communication difficulties inherent in autism are result of a hidden grammar system taught using methods incompatible with how autistic minds work. 

### 4.2 Research-Grounded

Every empirical claim in the hub traces to a peer-reviewed source, a published book, or is explicitly labeled as community knowledge or lived experience. The hub is built on the academic pragmatics literature (Austin, Grice, Searle, Brown & Levinson, Sperber & Wilson, Clark, Levinson, and their successors) and on the autism research that corrects and extends it (Milton, Crompton, Sasson, and others). When a claim is speculative, the hub says so.

### 4.3 Evidence-Quality-Labeled

Not all evidence is the same. The hub distinguishes between large replicated findings, small studies, theoretical claims, clinical observations, and community consensus. Where the evidence is strong, specific studies are cited. Where the evidence is weak or contested, the hub says so out loud. You should not have to guess how confident to be in a given claim.

### 4.4 Not a Masking Manual

The hub does not teach you to perform neurotypicality. It does not tell you to make more eye contact, soften your voice, smile more, or match others' body language because that is what "successful" communication looks like. It teaches you how pragmatics works so that you can make informed decisions about when, how, and whether to engage with each piece of it. The goal is literacy, not camouflage.

This matters because there is now robust evidence that sustained masking is associated with exhaustion, burnout, depression, anxiety, and suicidality in autistic adults (Cage & Troxell-Whitman, 2019; Cassidy et al., 2020). A learning resource that trains you to mask harder is not a safe learning resource. The hub is explicitly not that.

### 4.5 Honest About Limits

Some pragmatic questions don't have clean answers. Some autistic communities are seriously under-researched -- especially autistic adults without intellectual disability, autistic women, autistic people of color, and late-diagnosed autistic adults. Some strategies work for some people and not others. Some categories in the hub rest on strong evidence, and some rest on thinner ground. The hub will tell you which is which.

### 4.6 Safety Before Engagement

Pragmatic asymmetry can be weaponized. The same indirectness that makes ordinary conversation hard to decode can be used, deliberately, to trap autistic people into accepting things they would never consent to if they had been told directly. The hub includes a dedicated manipulation sub-hub for this reason. When stakes are high -- when safety is at risk, when coercive control may be present, when a situation may be escalating -- the hub's first move is **safety planning**, not strategy. You will see this reflected in how the manipulation pages are ordered: safety assessment comes before pattern recognition, because a pattern you recognize while unsafe is less useful than a plan to get safe first.

