## 5. How to Read This Hub

The hub is organized into tiers. You do not have to read it in order, but the tiers tell you which pages assume what.

### 5.1 The Map

| Tier | What It Contains | Read When |
|------|------------------|-----------|
| **Tier 1 -- Framing** | This page + Cooperative Principle, Relevance Theory, Double Empathy | First. These set the frame for everything else. |
| **Tier 2 -- Core mechanisms** | Categories 01-10: Speech Acts, Implicature, Politeness, Conversation Structure, Discourse Markers, Hedging, Register, Deixis, Presupposition, Relevance Theory | After Tier 1. The load-bearing pragmatic systems. |
| **Tier 3 -- Extended pragmatics** | Categories 11-17: Non-literal Language, Narrative, Topic Management, Nonverbal Pragmatics, Prosody, Common Ground, Questions | When you want depth. These build on Tier 2. |
| **Tier 4 -- Applied & social** | Categories 18-24: Refusal & Disagreement, Phatic Communication, Digital Pragmatics, Specific Contexts, Social Hierarchy, Information Structure, Logical Fallacies | When you have specific situations to apply the system to. |
| **Stage 1 Deep Dives** | Information Structure, Logical Fallacies, Pragmatic Manipulation (the last is superseded in depth by the sub-hub) | For additional depth on these three topics. |
| **Manipulation Sub-Hub** | 40 pages covering safety, patterns, strategies, and context | When stakes are high or when a specific pattern needs to be recognized. Start at Safety Assessment. |

### 5.2 Linear or Jump-Around

Both are fine.

**If you want to read linearly**, start with the three other Tier 1 pages (Cooperative Principle, Relevance Theory, Double Empathy), then move to Category 01 (Speech Acts) and work through the Tier 2 categories in order. This gives you the foundational system in roughly the order pragmatics developed historically.

**If you are here for a specific need**, use these entry points:

- **Workplace breakdowns**: Start with [Category 03 -- Politeness](category-03-politeness.md), then [Category 18 -- Refusal & Disagreement](category-18-refusal-disagreement.md), then [Category 21 -- Specific Contexts](category-21-specific-contexts.md).
- **Friendships and relationships**: Start with [Category 02 -- Implicature](category-02-implicature.md), then [Category 19 -- Phatic Communication](category-19-phatic-communication.md), then [Category 16 -- Common Ground](category-16-common-ground.md).
- **Recognizing when something is wrong**: Start with [Manipulation sub-hub Safety Assessment](manipulation-hub-safety-assessment.md), then [Miscommunication vs Manipulation](manipulation-hub-miscommunication-vs-manipulation.md).
- **Understanding why conversations keep going sideways**: Start with [Tier 1 -- Double Empathy](tier-1-double-empathy.md), then [Category 04 -- Conversation Structure](category-04-conversation-structure.md).
- **Making sense of indirectness**: Start with [Category 01 -- Speech Acts](category-01-speech-acts.md), then [Category 02 -- Implicature](category-02-implicature.md).

### 5.3 A Note on Density

Some categories are long. That is on purpose. Pragmatics is a real system with real mechanics, and flattening it into bullet points would misrepresent how much is actually going on. The hub errs on the side of explaining rather than summarizing. If a section is dense, skim it first, read it once, and come back. Nothing in the hub is written to be understood in one pass. You are not behind if a page takes you a few sessions.

---

## 6. What This Page Is Not

A few things this page is deliberately not, so you know what to expect from the rest of the hub.

- **It is not a complete introduction to pragmatics.** Category 01 onwards is the actual introduction. This page is the door.
- **It is not a list of rules to memorize.** Pragmatics is a system with internal logic. Memorization is not the point; pattern recognition is.
- **It is not a diagnosis or a treatment plan.** Nothing here replaces a clinician, a therapist, or a friend who knows you. This is a learning resource.
- **It is not a promise that learning pragmatics will fix all social difficulty.** Some difficulty is the double empathy problem and will persist no matter how well you understand the non-autistic side of the mismatch. Some difficulty is about specific environments being hostile to autistic communication. Learning the system gives you more options, not a guaranteed smooth ride.
- **It is not a guide to performing neurotypicality.** Again: the hub is literacy, not masking.

---

## 7. Key Takeaways

Five things to carry with you into the rest of the hub.

1. **Pragmatics is a real system.** It has mechanics, patterns, and names. It is not magic, it is not instinct, and it is not something that some people just *have*.

2. **You didn't fail to learn it. You weren't taught it.** The implicit channel most people learned through is narrower for autistic cognition, and the explicit channel -- actual spoken-aloud instruction -- was almost never offered. The hub is the explicit channel.

3. **The gap is bidirectional.** Autistic and non-autistic speakers operate with different pragmatic expectations, and the breakdowns between them belong to both sides (Milton, 2012). You are not the broken half of the conversation.

4. **Learning pragmatics is not the same as performing neurotypicality.** You are allowed to understand a politeness move without doing it. The point is to have the choice.

5. **You decide what to do with the system.** The hub is documentation for software you have to interact with. What you run, how you run it, and when you refuse to run it at all -- those are yours.

---

## 8. Where to Go Next

Four natural next steps from here, depending on what you want.

- **If you want the rest of the framing first**, read the other three Tier 1 pages in this order: [Cooperative Principle](tier-1-cooperative-principle.md), [Relevance Theory](tier-1-relevance-theory.md), [Double Empathy](tier-1-double-empathy.md). That gives you the full frame before you touch a category.

- **If you want to get into the actual system**, go to [Category 01 -- Speech Acts](category-01-speech-acts.md). It is the historical and conceptual foundation of pragmatics, and it makes everything else easier.

- **If you want the single most practically useful category first**, go to [Category 02 -- Implicature](category-02-implicature.md). Implicature is where most everyday mismatches happen, and reading Category 2 early pays off immediately.

- **If you are reading this because something is going wrong and you need to know whether it is serious**, go to [Manipulation sub-hub -- Safety Assessment](manipulation-hub-safety-assessment.md). That page comes before any strategy. If lethality indicators are present (strangulation, separation contemplation, weapons access, escalating control), stop and contact a trained advocate before doing anything else.

