## Sources

This is an intro page, so the reference list is short. Every claim made here is developed at length, with full citations, in the category it belongs to.

**Foundational pragmatics**

- Austin, J.L. (1962). *How to Do Things with Words*. Harvard University Press. [Founding text of speech act theory. Introduces the performative / constative distinction and then dismantles it.] [Amazon](https://www.amazon.com/How-Things-Words-J-Austin/dp/0674411528)
- Grice, H.P. (1975). "Logic and Conversation." In *Syntax and Semantics, Vol. 3*. Academic Press. [Introduces the Cooperative Principle, the conversational maxims, and conversational implicature.] [PDF](https://www.ucl.ac.uk/ls/studypacks/Grice-Logic.pdf)
- Searle, J.R. (1969). *Speech Acts: An Essay in the Philosophy of Language*. Cambridge University Press. [Systematic development of Austin's framework. Source of the direct / indirect speech act distinction.] [Amazon](https://www.amazon.com/Speech-Acts-Essay-Philosophy-Language/dp/052109626X)
- Brown, P. & Levinson, S. (1987). *Politeness: Some Universals in Language Usage*. Cambridge University Press. [The face-based theory of politeness that underwrites Category 3.] [Amazon](https://www.amazon.com/Politeness-Universals-Language-Interactional-Sociolinguistics/dp/0521313554)

**Autism-pragmatics research**

- Milton, D. (2012). "On the ontological status of autism: the 'double empathy problem'." *Disability & Society*, 27(6), 883-887. [The load-bearing paper for this hub's framing of pragmatic mismatch as bidirectional.] [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1080/09687599.2012.710008) [paywalled]
- Crompton, C.J., Ropar, D., Evans-Williams, C.V., Flynn, E.G., & Fletcher-Watson, S. (2020). "Autistic peer-to-peer information transfer is highly effective." *Autism*, 24(7), 1704-1712. [Empirical support for the double empathy claim: autistic-to-autistic communication is efficient.] [PMC](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7545656/)
- Cage, E. & Troxell-Whitman, Z. (2019). "Understanding the reasons, contexts and costs of camouflaging for autistic adults." *Journal of Autism and Developmental Disorders*, 49(5), 1899-1911. [Evidence on the costs of masking, which grounds Commitment 4.4.] [Springer](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10803-018-03878-x) [paywalled]
- Cassidy, S.A. et al. (2020). "Is camouflaging autistic traits associated with suicidal thoughts and behaviours? Expanding the interpersonal psychological theory of suicide in an undergraduate student sample." *Journal of Autism and Developmental Disorders*, 50(10), 3638-3648. [Further evidence on masking and mental health outcomes.] [Springer](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10803-019-04323-3) [paywalled]

Full citations and evidence-quality notes live in the research files that accompany each category.

